Less than 100 rounds through this shotgun. It will shoot 2 3/4 or 3" shells. Like new condition and comes in original box with manuals and other Benelli swag. Additional M3 Information The Benelli M3 is an updated version of the Benelli M1 shotgun. M3 uses sameinertia recoil semi-automatic system as earlier Benelli M1,but with addition of the another Benelli patented feature, which allows to the shooter to lock the semi-automatic action and switch to the manually operated pump-action mode and back in the matter of seconds. The action type switch is located at the forward end of the forearm, and is formed as an annular knurledring. Rotation of this ring either engages the action rods of the pump system and locks the semi-automatic recoil system, or disengages the action bars, locks the forearm and allows the inertia recoil system to operate the action automatically. This greatly improves the versatility of the shotgun, allowing itto fire low-powered ammunition (mostly of special purpose, such as less-lethal rubber or tear-gas projectiles) in the manually operated pump action mode, and to fire full power combat loads with slugs or buckshot in rapid semi-automatic mode.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Converted 7.62x39 Saiga, AK, AKM, AK47, AK-47
postcontent:
Greetings, comrades. For sale is a Saiga chambered in 7.62x39, made by Izhmash in Mother Russia, and converted with a proper pistol grip and includes the correct number of US-made parts for compliance with 922r and to allow the use of foreign standard capacity 30-round magazines.

If you're looking for an AK, don't get a crappy WASR or equivalent for the same price. Look into some other variants in this price range and you might find thin US-made non mil-spec barrels estimated to have a lifespan of only 10k rounds before degradation. Looks like the other option is to spring 1200+ for a more expensive rifle such as an Arsenal, Krebs, RifleDynamics, etc..

I will sell to Wisconsin residents only, for cash, face-to-face. I would be willing to drive maybe an hour or two. If you're in the Eau Claire area, I typically go to the range once or twice a week and would be willing to bring it along some time if you wanted to stop out and take a look at it.

I'll include a standard capacity 30-round mil-spec magazine with it. All rounds fired through it have been non-corrosive Wolf, Golden Tiger, brown/silver bear. I haven't fired this rifle in some time because I did a full conversion on a 5.45x39 and that has became my lead-slinger of choice.

The Saiga includes:
- Tapco SAW pistol grip, G2 trigger, Galil handgaurd
- Mojo Microclick peep sight
- Dinzag Arms bolt-on handguard retainer
- DPH Arms clip-on flash hider (this was temporary, I had planned on threading the barrel but never got around to it)
- Romanian wire-folding stock (these went for $75 to $100 when I bought it, if I remember correctly. If you plan on replacing the stock you could probably sell this for a good price nowadays.)

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  `S&W Schofield Russian Model 3 Revolver
postcontent: The Smith & Wesson Schofield Russian Model 3 Revolver was a single-action, cartridge-firing, top-break revolver produced by Smith & Wesson from 1870 to 1915. "Russian Model", so named because it was supplied to military of the Russian Empire (20,000 No. 3's were ordered in .44 caliber by the Imperial Russian Army in 1871),The S&W Model 3 was originally chambered for the .44 S&W American and .44 Russian cartridges, and typically did not have the cartridge information stamped on the gun (as is standard practice for most commercial firearms).Smith & Wesson produced large numbers of the Model 3, in three distinct models, for the Russian Empire by special order. The first was the 1st Model Russian (the original order design), and the Russian Ordnance Inspector mandated a number of improvements to the design, resulting in the 2nd Model Russian, with a final revision to the Russian design being known as the 3rd Model Russian. Smith & Wesson nearly went bankrupt as a result of their Russian Contract production, as the Imperial government assigned a number of engineers and gunsmiths to reverse-engineer the Smith & Wesson design, and then began to produce copies of the revolver—both in their own arsenal at Tula and by contracting other manufacturers in Germany and elsewhere in Europe to manufacture copies of the revolver …...PLEASE check your state and local gun laws on purchasing this item BEFORE BIDDING.
